3.188. 
Transactions relating to the property of a minor child 
1. Without the prior authorisation of the court, the parents may not:
1) transfer, mortgage or otherwise encumber the property of their minor children; 
2) accept or refuse to accept an inheritance in the name of their minor children; 
3) enter into a lease of the minor children's property for a term exceeding five years; 
4) enter into an arbitration agreement in the name of the minor children; 
5) enter into a loan agreement in the name of the minor children, provided that the amount of the agreement exceeds the equivalent of four times the minimum wage; or 
6) invest the minor children's money, provided that the amount of the money exceeds the equivalent of 10 times the minimum wages.
2. If a conflict of interest arises between minor children of the same parents or between a minor child and his or her parents in the context of a transaction, the court shall, at the request of either parent, appoint an ad hoc guardian for the transaction. 
3. Where there is a conflict of interests between a minor child and one of his or her parents, the interests of the child shall be represented and the transaction shall be concluded by the parent between whom and the child there is no conflict of interests. 
4. In the event of a breach of the rules set out in paragraphs 1, 2 and 3 of this Article, the transaction may be declared null and void upon an action brought by the child, one of the child's parents, or their heirs 5. The prior authorisation of the court shall not be required for the conclusion of the transactions referred to in paragraph 1 of this Article when the transaction is concluded in notarial form. Before approving the transaction, the notary shall assess, in accordance with the procedure laid down by the Notarial Law, whether the conclusion of the transaction will adequately protect the rights and interests of the minor child.
